<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} is a particle which is indicates which carries the idea of only or of "just done", "just doing" or "about to do".
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="just-happened">@Vta{{}}</a>@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} indicates that something has just happened or has just been done. It is the
speaker's feeling that determines whether the action is recent or not.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{sakki@KJ{{daytime}}gohanwo@KJ{{eat}}beta@EM{{bakari}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I had lunch just a little while ago.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="happening">@Vte{{}}</a>@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} indicates that something is being done, with a nuance that nothing else is being done.
The action is happening habitually or repeatedly and the speaker is critical or dissatisfied.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{springtime^creek}}ha@KJ{{cry}}te@EM{{bakari}}ite@KJ{{what}}mo@KJ{{tale}}soutoshinai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Harue is crying and won't talk about anything.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="happening-noun">When</a> used with a transitive verb, the same feeling can be conveyed with the
sentence pattern @N{{}}@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}@Vte{{}}iru}}.


<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{younger*brother}}haitsumo@KT{{konpyu-ta-ge-mu}}@EM{{bakari}}shiteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Almost all my younger brother does is play computer games.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="about-to-happen">@Vru{{}}</a>@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} indicates that something is about to be done.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono@KT{{repo-to}}haato@KJ{{tie^argument}}wo@KJ{{write}}ku@EM{{bakari}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The only thing left to do with this report is to write a conclusion.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="one-direction">@Vru{{}}</a>@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} can indicate that something changes and continues to change in a specific direction.
Often the change is not seen as positive.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{konogoro@KJ{{attend^matter}}ga@KJ{{many}}kute@FG{{@KJ{{remainder^profession}}:zangyou}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{increase}}:fu}}eru@EM{{bakari}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Recently there is so much work that overtime just keeps increasing.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="habitual">@Vte{{}}</a>@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}iru}} indicates that something is being done habitually or repeatedly and the speaker is critical or disatisfied.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono@FG{{@KJ{{cat}}:neko}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{one^day^in}}:ichinichijuu}},@FG{{@KJ{{lie*down}}:ne}}te@EM{{bakari}}iru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    This cat just sleeps all day long.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
With a transitive verb the formation <a name="habitual-trans">@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}}@Vte{{}}</a>@HI{{iru}} may be used.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{younger*brother}}:otouto}}haitsumokonpyu-ta-ge-mu@EM{{bakari}}shiteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Almost all my younger brother does is play computer games.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In classical Japanese @HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} expressed the speaker's conjecture and this is still seen
in @QNTF{{}} @HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}}, which means "about".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{ten^person}}@EM{{bakari}}no@KJ{{friend^accomplished}}ga@KJ{{hand^transmit}}ttekuremashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    About 10 friends helped me.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="denai">@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}denai}}</a> expresses the idea of "not also but also". In this usage it can be replaced by
<a href="grammar-particle-dake.html">@HI{{dake}}</a> but @HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} is slightly more emphatic.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{England^word}}@EM{{bakari}}denaku,@KT{{furansu}}@KJ{{word}}mo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}shitaindesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I want to study not only English but French too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} emphasises the singularity of the immediately preceding word.
</p>
<p>
The position of @HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} slightly changes the meaning, so several versions of a sentence are
supplied to show the difference.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{chapter^long}}:kachou}}hakono@KJ{{time}}@KT{{uisuki-}}@EM{{bakari}}@KJ{{drink}}ndeimasune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The section chief is drinking nothing but whiskey these days.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{chapter^long}}:kachou}}hakono@KJ{{time}}@KT{{uisuki-}}wo@KJ{{drink}}nde@EM{{bakari}}imasune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The section chief is doing nothing but drinking whiskey these days.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{chapter^long}}:kachou}}hakono@KJ{{time}}@KT{{uisuki-}}@KJ{{drink}}ndeiru@EM{{bakari}}desune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    All the section chief does these days is drink whiskey.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{bakarini}}}} emphasises a reason or a cause.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{transit^environs}}:watanabe}}sanha@KT{{sutereo}}wo@KJ{{buy}}itai@EM{{bakarini}},
    @FG{{@KJ{{one^life^suspend^fate}}:isshoukenmei}}ni@KT{{arubaito}}woshiteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Watanabe is working like a dog at his part-time job because he wants to buy a stereo so badly.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When @HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} follows @HI{{ga}} or @HI{{wo}}, these particles drop. When it follows
@HI{{ni}} or @HI{{he}}, these particles may optionally drop. Other particles remain.
</p>

